04780nam a22005655i 9780774851718DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748517187 a10.59962/97807748517182doi  a(DE-B1597)662106  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE4381.5.K45 2005eb 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a3421 aKelly, James B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGoverning with the Charter :bLegislative and Judicial Activism and Framers' Intent /cJames B. Kelly. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2006] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms -- tIntroduction -- tDemocratic Activism and Constitutional Politics -- tDemocracy and Judicial Review -- tConstitutional Politics and the Charter -- tFramers’ Intent and the Parliamentary Arena -- tJudicial Activism and the Supreme Court of Canada -- tThe Supreme Court and Police Conduct -- tGuardians of the Constitution -- tLegislative Activism and the Policy Process -- tThe Charter and Canadian Federalism -- tGoverning with the Charter of Rights -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the introduction of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms in 1982, the question of judicial power and its relationship to parliamentary democracy has been an important one in Canadian politics. Some critics, suspicious of what they perceive as the "activism" of "unelected and unaccountable" judges, view the increased power of the Supreme Court as a direct challenge to parliament. But has parliamentary democracy been weakened by judicial responses to the Charter? In Governing with the Charter, James Kelly clearly demonstrates that our current democratic deficit is not the result of the Supreme Court's judicial activism. On the contrary, an activist framers' intent surrounds the Charter, and the Supreme Court has simply, and appropriately, responded to this new constitutional environment. While the Supreme Court is admittedly a political actor, it is not the sole interpreter of the Charter, as the court, the cabinet, and bureaucracy all respond to the document, which has ensured the proper functioning of constitutional supremacy in Canada. Kelly analyzes the parliamentary hearings on the Charter and also draws from interviews with public servants, senators, and members of parliament actively involved in appraising legislation to ensure that it is consistent with the Charter. He concludes that the principal institutional outcome of the Charter has been a marginalization of Parliament and that this is due to the Prime Minister's decision on how to govern with the Charter. A significant contribution to law and society studies, Governing with the Charter will be widely read by political scientists, legal scholars, parliamentarians, public servants, and students of the machinery of government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJudicial powerzCanada. 0aLegislative powerzCanada. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzCanada. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485171840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774851718423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774851718/original  a978-3-11-